{"PubmedArticle":[{"MedlineCitation":{"@attributes":{"Status":"MEDLINE","Owner":"NLM"},"PMID":"25376883","DateCompleted":{"Year":"2017","Month":"01","Day":"26"},"DateRevised":{"Year":"2017","Month":"01","Day":"26"},"Article":{"@attributes":{"PubModel":"Print-Electronic"},"Journal":{"ISSN":"1741-2684","JournalIssue":{"@attributes":{"CitedMedium":"Internet"},"Volume":"15","Issue":"5","PubDate":{"Year":"2016","Month":"Sep"}},"Title":"Dementia (London, England)","ISOAbbreviation":"Dementia (London)"},"ArticleTitle":"Changes in communication of Deaf people with dementia: A thematic interview with a close family member.","Pagination":{"MedlinePgn":"1205-18"},"ELocationID":"10.1177\/1471301214557183","Abstract":{"AbstractText":["Learning about changes in communication of Deaf with dementia (DWD) is important in order to improve services and support DWD and their families. We explored family members' views on the changes in communication DWD have and the ways communication was adapted due to progression of dementia.","A qualitative content analysis of thematic interviews that were conducted with eight close family members of DWD.","With decreasing vocabulary and increasing sign-finding difficulties, conversations became poorer, and DWD tended to diverge from the topic. Nonverbal communication became more important as the verbal communication abilities of DWD deteriorated, and the adult children took a more active role by taking initiative and guiding conversations.","DWD seem to go through similar changes in communication as hearing people with dementia. Adult children of DWD need to get used to interpreting and assisting their parent's communication through different phases of dementia."],"CopyrightInformation":"\u00a9 The Author(s) 2014."},"AuthorList":{"@attributes":{"CompleteYN":"Y"},"Author":[{"@attributes":{"ValidYN":"Y"},"LastName":"Rantap\u00e4\u00e4","ForeName":"Minna","Initials":"M","AffiliationInfo":{"Affiliation":"Institute of Health Sciences, the University of Oulu, Oulu, Finland minna.rantapaa@sieppijarvi.fi."}},{"@attributes":{"ValidYN":"Y"},"LastName":"Pekkala","ForeName":"Seija","Initials":"S","AffiliationInfo":{"Affiliation":"Institute of Behavioural Sciences, University of Helsinki, Helsinki, Finland."}}]},"Language":"eng","PublicationTypeList":{"PublicationType":"Journal Article"},"ArticleDate":{"@attributes":{"DateType":"Electronic"},"Year":"2014","Month":"11","Day":"06"}},"MedlineJournalInfo":{"Country":"England","MedlineTA":"Dementia (London)","NlmUniqueID":"101128698","ISSNLinking":"1471-3012"},"CitationSubset":"IM","MeshHeadingList":{"MeshHeading":[{"DescriptorName":"Adult"},{"DescriptorName":"Aged"},{"DescriptorName":"Caregivers","QualifierName":"psychology"},{"DescriptorName":"Deafness","QualifierName":["complications","psychology"]},{"DescriptorName":"Dementia","QualifierName":["complications","psychology"]},{"DescriptorName":"Family Relations","QualifierName":"psychology"},{"DescriptorName":"Female"},{"DescriptorName":"Humans"},{"DescriptorName":"Male"},{"DescriptorName":"Middle Aged"},{"DescriptorName":"Needs Assessment"},{"DescriptorName":"Persons With Hearing Impairments","QualifierName":"psychology"},{"DescriptorName":"Qualitative Research"},{"DescriptorName":"Sign Language"}]},"KeywordList":{"@attributes":{"Owner":"NOTNLM"},"Keyword":["communication","dementia","nonverbal communication","qualitative content analysis","sign language"]}},"PubmedData":{"History":{"PubMedPubDate":[{"@attributes":{"PubStatus":"entrez"},"Year":"2014","Month":"11","Day":"8","Hour":"6","Minute":"0"},{"@attributes":{"PubStatus":"pubmed"},"Year":"2014","Month":"11","Day":"8","Hour":"6","Minute":"0"},{"@attributes":{"PubStatus":"medline"},"Year":"2017","Month":"1","Day":"27","Hour":"6","Minute":"0"}]},"PublicationStatus":"ppublish","ArticleIdList":{"ArticleId":["25376883","1471301214557183","10.1177\/1471301214557183"]}}},{"MedlineCitation":{"@attributes":{"Status":"MEDLINE","Owner":"NLM"},"PMID":"23985011","DateCompleted":{"Year":"2014","Month":"06","Day":"17"},"DateRevised":{"Year":"2019","Month":"12","Day":"20"},"Article":{"@attributes":{"PubModel":"Print-Electronic"},"Journal":{"ISSN":"1464-5076","JournalIssue":{"@attributes":{"CitedMedium":"Internet"},"Volume":"27","Issue":"12","PubDate":{"Year":"2013","Month":"Dec"}},"Title":"Clinical linguistics & phonetics","ISOAbbreviation":"Clin Linguist Phon"},"ArticleTitle":"Lexical retrieval in discourse: an early indicator of Alzheimer's dementia.","Pagination":{"MedlinePgn":"905-21"},"ELocationID":"10.3109\/02699206.2013.815278","Abstract":{"AbstractText":"We examined the progression of lexical-retrieval deficits in individuals with neuropathologically determined Alzheimer's disease (AD; n = 23) and a comparison group without criteria for AD (n = 24) to determine whether linguistic changes were a significant marker of the disease. Our participants underwent multiple administrations of a neuropsychological battery, with initial administration occurring on average 16 years prior to death. The battery included the Boston Naming Test (BNT), a letter fluency task (FAS) and written description of the Cookie Theft Picture (CTP). Repeated measures analysis revealed that the AD-group showed progressively greater decline in FAS and CTP lexical performance than the comparison group. Cross-sectional time-specific group comparisons indicated that the CTP differentiated performance between the two groups at 7-9 years prior to death and FAS and BNT only at 2-4 years. These results suggest that lexical-retrieval deficits in written discourse serve as an early indicator of AD."},"AuthorList":{"@attributes":{"CompleteYN":"Y"},"Author":[{"@attributes":{"ValidYN":"Y"},"LastName":"Pekkala","ForeName":"Seija","Initials":"S","AffiliationInfo":{"Affiliation":"Institute of Behavioural Sciences, University of Helsinki , Helsinki , Finland ."}},{"@attributes":{"ValidYN":"Y"},"LastName":"Wiener","ForeName":"Debra","Initials":"D"},{"@attributes":{"ValidYN":"Y"},"LastNam